Bio security measures are being stepped up at Brisbane International Airport after exotic mosquitoes were found on three separate occasions . 
  Planes coming from South-East Asian countries are being routinely fumigated . 
  Aedes aegypti is known to carry crippling diseases like dengue and chikunguya . 
  The blood suckers were discovered in the international baggage terminal on February 17, March 30 and again on March 31 . 
  In February authorities were forced to step up bio security at Perth, Adelaide and Brisbane airports . 
 